{
  "text": "For enzymatic activity, lung rudiments and fibroblasts were homogenized in 2 ml (tissue) or in 1 ml (fibroblasts) of 0.1 M citrate/0.2 M phosphate buffer, pH 4.5, then centrifuged at 25,000 g for 10 min and the supernatants were used. In preliminary experiments, no enzymatic activity was detected in the sediments. \u00df-N-acetyl-glucosaminidase (EC 3.2.1.30), \u00df-D-glucuronidase (EC 3.2.1.31), \u00df-Nacetyl-galactosaminidase (EC 3.2.1.53) and \u00df-galactosidase (EC 3.2.1.23) were assayed as previously described by [CITATION_1] using, respectively, as substrates 4-methyl-umbelliferyl-\u00df-N-acetyl glucosaminide, 4-methyl-umbelliferyl-\u00df-D-glucuronide, 4-methyl-umbelliferil-\u00df-N-acetylgalactosaminide 4-methyl-umbelliferyl-\u00df-galactoside in 0.1 M citrate/0.2 M phosphate buffer, pH 4.5, and 50 \u00b5l of enzyme preparation. One enzyme unit is defined as the amount of the enzyme that converts 1 nmol/hr of substrate into 4-methyl-umbelliferone at 37\u00b0C. Specific activity is expressed as units/mg protein. Proteins were determined according to the Bradford method (1976) using cristalline calf gamma globuline (Merck) as standard.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "8583600"
  },
  "bib_entries": {
    "8583600": {
      "title": "A distinct \u00df-hexosaminidase isoenzyme separated from human leukemic lymphocytes and myelocytes",
      "abstract": "The beta-hexosaminidase (EC 3.2.1.30) isoenzymes were separated on the basis of their carbohydrate moieties by an affinity chromatography using immobilized phenylboronate. Normal lymphocytes and granulocytes contain two major forms of beta-hexosaminidase, acute lymphoblastic, acute myeloblastic, chronic lymphocytic and chronic myelocytic leukemic cells contain an extra, distinct isoenzyme of beta-hexosaminidase. This extra isoenzyme may be a marker for the leukemic conversion of hematopoietic tissue."
    }
  }
}